-1973 continues her personal and anecdotal history of Wilfrid Laurier University. This memoir picks up the story following the institutions transition from Waterloo College, a small college affiliated with the University of Western Ontario, to the independent Waterloo Lutheran University. Documenting student demonstrations and faculty unrest of the 1960s as well as the university’s evolution from a religious to a secular institution, this illustrated book will appeal not only to alumni but to those interested in the history of Kitchener-Waterloo and of postsecondary education in Ontario. The royalties from the sale of this book will be directed towards funding scholarships.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollege teachersxBiographyxOntarioxWaterloo. 0aCollege teacherszOntariozWaterloovBiography. 0aProfesseurs (Enseignement supérieur)xBiographiesxOntarioxWaterlooxOntarioxWaterloo. 4aEducation. 4aWaterloo Region. 4aWilfrid Laurier University. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Educators.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458124540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554581245423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554581245/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles